JudgmentText.P:
6. The short question that was, in the above backdrop, argued by learned counsel for the parties at considerable length was whether the proceedings instituted by the deceased-owners of the demised property could be continued by the legal heirs left behind by them. Mr. K.V. Vishwanathan, learned senior counsel, appearing for the legal heirs of the deceased-appellant contended that it was permissible for the legal heirs to continue the present proceedings and seek eviction of the tenant on the basis of the requirement pleaded by the erstwhile owners in the eviction petition filed by them. The rights and obligations of the parties, argued Mr. Vishwanathan, get crystallized as on the date of the filing of the petition. Any subsequent development, according to the learned counsel, would be irrelevant to the maintainability or the continuance of the proceedings after the death of the original petitioners. Reliance in support of that submission was placed by the learned counsel upon the decisions of this Court in Shamshad Ahmad vs. Tilak Raj Bajaj (2008 (9) SCC 1 


			2008 ILO SC 1469
		), Maganlal Vs. Nanasaheb (2008 (13) SCC 758 


			2008 ILO SC 2084
		), Pratap Rai Tanwani Vs. Uttam Chand (2004 (8) SCC 490 


			2004 ILO SC 778
		), Gaya Prasad Vs. Pradeep Srivastava (2001 (2) SCC 604 


			2001 ILO SC 20301
		), Kamleshwar Prasad Vs. Pradumanju Agarwal (1997 (4) SCC 413 


			1997 ILO SC 823
		), Shakuntala Bai Vs. Narayan Das (2004 (5) SCC 772 


			2004 ILO SC 384
		), G.C. Kapoor Vs. Nand Kumar Bhasin (2002 (1) SCC 610 


			2001 ILO SC 20375
		) and Shantilal Thakordas Vs. Chimanlal Maganlal Telwala (1976 (4) SCC 417 


			1976 ILO SC 175
		).

7. On behalf of the respondent-tenants Mr. L. Nageswara Rao, learned senior counsel, placed heavy reliance on the decisions of this Court in Pasupuleti Venkateswarlu Vs. Motor and General Traders (1975 (1) SCC 770 


			1975 ILO SC 408
		), Om Prakash Gupta Vs. Ranbir B. Goyal (2002 (2) SCC 256 


			2002 ILO SC 34
		), Hasmat Rai Vs. Raghunath Prasad (1981 (3) SCC 103 


			1981 ILO SC 514
		) and Baba Kashinath Bhinge Vs. Samast Lingayat Gavali (1994 Supp (3) SCC 698 


			1993 ILO SC 693
		). It was argued by Mr. Rao that the legal position as to whether the Court could take note of the subsequent developments stood settled by the above decisions which left no manner of doubt that all such developments as have an impact on the rights and obligations of the parties must be taken into consideration by the Court and the relief suitably moulded.

